The start symbol S has only one production:

S → NT43 NT61

Therefore any string in the language must consist of the concatenation of whatever NT43 derives followed by whatever NT61 derives.

NT61 has exactly one production:

NT61 → 't33'

Hence the second (and final) token of every string generated by the grammar must be t33.

The string we are testing ends with t42, not t33. Consequently it cannot be produced by this grammar.

Because every derivation from the start symbol begins with  
S → NT43 NT61 → (tokens generated by NT43) followed immediately by the single terminal produced by NT61, and NT61 can only produce the terminal t33, any string generated by the grammar must end with t33.  

The given string ends with t42, not t33, so it cannot be generated by the grammar.
